    summary: "In 1993, Dutch developers Team Hoi created the platformer *Moon Child* for the Amiga, but it was never released. A recent resurgence of interest online has prompted designer Metin Seven to rejoin social media and engage with fans.",
    body: "In 1993, Dutch developers Team Hoi started working on the Amiga platformer *Moon Child*, featuring a green space lad and his dinosaur-like friend. The game was never released on Amiga, and its 1997 PC port saw only limited distribution. After years of being available online, a recent post from Games That Weren't ignited a wave of fanfare, bringing the original creators back to social media.\n\nDesigner Metin Seven re-registered his account to join in on the memes and expressed his enthusiasm. He said he enjoyed reading fan creations and shared them with composer Ramon Braumuller. \"I\u2019m having so much fun reading and viewing all the *Moon Child* love,\" Seven posted.\n\nThe game itself is a blend of vibrant, peculiar elements typical of the Amiga era. It features fast-paced, floaty gameplay, resembling a dreamlike experience influenced by classics like *Super Mario*. After attempting to pitch the game to publishers like Psygnosis, Team Hoi shifted to creating a PC version when Commodore and the Amiga faded from the market. However, limited resources meant its 1997 release was restricted to the Netherlands.\n\nThe nostalgia for *Moon Child* surged recently due in part to its iconic demo music. The theme track, with striking phrases like \u201cThe story is true\u201d and \u201cYou\u2019ve got the power to be his friend,\u201d captivated listeners and inspired artistic chaos online. From fan art to remixes, the outpouring of creativity from fans highlights a connection with a game that almost never made it.\n\nIn just a few days, the online conversation around *Moon Child* exploded. Seven has embraced this renewed interest by sharing behind-the-scenes content, including concept art and design documents. These treasures promise to give *Moon Child* a second chance to shine, far beyond the limited scope of its original launch.",
