    body: "Alyx Jones, founder of Silver Script Games, feels sidelined after her game The Quiet Things was cut from the BAFTA Game Awards showcase due to its sensitive content. The narrative game focuses on Jones\u2019s personal experiences with mental health and childhood trauma.\n\nIn a LinkedIn post, Jones detailed how she received a call the night before the awards informing her that the trailer was pulled. Organizers stated there wasn't enough time to provide necessary warnings for the audience. Jones expressed frustration, claiming her offers to make adjustments were met with silence.\n\n\u201cI\u2019m sick of it,\u201d she wrote. \u201cWhat has upset me so much is not just the decision, but how this happens to me over and over. Doors close because the subject matter might upset people or make them uncomfortable.\u201d She described The Quiet Things as an exploration of trauma and survival that aims to give a voice to those who have been silenced.\n\nThe BAFTA organization responded to the controversy, stating that the decision was made in consideration of its guests and emphasized their support for games addressing difficult themes. They noted that without sufficient warning, it was a compliance decision regarding the event's wellbeing.\n\nJones's experience highlights ongoing challenges in the gaming industry, where projects focusing on sensitive subjects frequently face barriers. As she continues to navigate these issues, the conversation around art, mental health, and the importance of sharing personal narratives remains critical.",
