    summary: "Job security in the gaming industry is declining, with significant layoffs contributing to a potential talent loss. Skillsearch's survey shows that approximately 40 percent of respondents have experienced layoffs, with over half occurring in the past year and 28 percent employed at studios that have made redundancies.",
    body: "Job security in the gaming industry has reached a critical point, threatening a brain drain of talent. External economic fears and rising costs often overshadow a more pressing issue: the long-term effects of widespread layoffs.\n\nSkillsearch's latest Salary and Satisfaction survey highlights these concerns, revealing that around 40 percent of respondents have faced layoffs. Over half of those were laid off in the past year, while an additional 28 percent work in studios that have made redundancies. These numbers suggest that a significant portion of the workforce feels the instability of their careers.\n\nRemote work continues to shape industry practices, yet its acceptance varies across studios. While fully remote work is rare, many employees now enjoy flexibility with a few days working from home. This shift challenges outdated notions surrounding office attendance and emphasizes the importance of workplace culture.\n\nThe survey data also underscores a troubling paradox. Though layoffs have made it seem like a hirer's market, hiring experienced talent remains difficult. Conversations with industry hiring professionals reveal a stark reality: skilled individuals are not as eager to pursue new opportunities due to fears about job security, despite the availability of positions.\n\nAs the gaming industry navigates these challenges, ensuring job security must become a priority. Without a commitment to creating stable work environments, the industry risks losing skilled professionals, which could hinder growth and innovation in the long run.",
